1 ABSTRACT :
1-1:Logics of knowledge and belief are often too static and inflexible to be used on real world problems .
1-2:In particular, they usually offer no concept for expressing that some course of events is more likely to happen than another .
1-3:We address this problem and extend CTLK (computation tree logic with knowledge) with a notion of plausibility, which allows for practical and counterfactual reasoning .
1-4:The new logic CTLKP (CTLK with plausibility) includes also a particular notion of belief .
1-5:A plausibility update operator is added to this logic in order to change plausibility assumptions dynamically .
1-6:Furthermore, we examine some important properties of these concepts .
1-7:In particular, we show that, for a natural class of models, belief is a KD45 modality .
1-8:We also show that model checking CTLKP is PTIME complete and can be done in time linear with respect to the size of models and formulae .
1-9:I.2.11 [Artificial Intelligence]: Distributed Artificial .
2 INTRODUCTION :
2-1:Notions like time, knowledge, and beliefs are very important for analyzing the behavior of agents and multi agent systems .
2-2:In this paper, we extend modal logics of time and knowledge with a concept of plausible behavior: this notion is added to the language of CTLK [19], which is a straightforward combination of the branching time temporal logic CTL [4, 3] and standard epistemic logic [9, 5] .
2-3:In our approach, plausibility can be seen as a temporal property of behaviors .
2-4:That is, some behaviors of the system can be assumed plausible and others implausible, with the underlying idea that the latter should perhaps be ignored in practical reasoning about possible future courses of action .
2-5:Moreover, behaviors can be formally understood as temporal paths in the Kripke structure modeling a multiagent system .
2-6:As a consequence, we obtain a language to reason about what can (or must) plausibly happen .
2-7:We propose a particular notion of beliefs (inspired by [20, 7]), defined in terms of epistemic relations and plausibility .
2-8:The main intuition is that beliefs are facts that an agent would know if he assumed that only plausible things could happen .
2-9:We believe that humans use such a concept of plausibility and practical beliefs quite often in their everyday reasoning .
2-10:Restricting one"s reasoning to plausible possibilities is essential to make the reasoning feasible, as the space of all possibilities is exceedingly large in real life .
2-11:We investigate some important properties of plausibility, knowledge, and belief in this new framework .
2-12:In particular, we show that knowledge is an S5 modality, and that beliefs satisfy axioms K45 in general, and KD45 for the class of plausibly serial models .
2-13:Finally, we show that the relationship between knowledge and belief for plausibly serial models is natural and reflects the initial intuition well .
2-14:We also show how plausibility assumptions can be specified in the object language via a plausibility update operator, and we study properties of such updates .
2-15:Finally, we show that model checking of the new logic is no more complex than model checking CTL and CTLK .
2-16:Our ultimate goal is to come up with a logic that allows the study of strategies, time, knowledge, and plausible rational behavior under both perfect and imperfect information .
2-17:As combining all these dimensions is highly nontrivial (cf .
2-18:[12, 14]) it seems reasonable to split this task .
2-19:While this paper deals with knowledge, plausibility, and belief, the companion paper [11] proposes a general framework for multi agent systems that regard game theoretical rationality criteria like Nash equilibrium, Pareto optimality, etc .
2-20:The latter approach is based on the more powerful logic ATL [1] .
2-21:The paper is structured as follows .
2-22:Firstly, we briefly present branching time logic with knowledge, CTLK .
2-23:In Section 3 we present our approach to plausibility and formally define CTLK with plausibility .
2-24:We also show how 582 978 81 904262 7 5 c 2007 IFAAMAS temporal formulae can be used to describe plausible paths, and we compare our logic with existing related work .
2-25:In Section 4, properties of knowledge, belief, and plausibility are explored .
2-26:Finally, we present verification complexity results for CTLKP in Section 5. .
3 BRANCHING TIME AND KNOWLEDGE :
3-1:In this paper we develop a framework for agents" beliefs about how the world can (or must) evolve .
3-2:Thus, we need a notion of time and change, plus a notion of what the agents are supposed to know in particular situations .
3-3:CTLK [19] is a straightforward combination of the computation tree logic CTL [4, 3] and standard epistemic logic [9, 5] .
3-4:CTL includes operators for temporal properties of systems: i.e., path quantifier E (there is a path), together with temporal operators: f(in the next state), 2 (always from now on) and U (until).1 Every occurrence of a temporal operator is preceded by exactly one path quantifier in CTL (this variant of the language is sometimes called vanilla CTL) .
3-5:Epistemic logic uses operators for representing agents" knowledge: Kaϕ is read as agent a knows that ϕ .
3-6:Let Π be a set of atomic propositions with a typical element p, and Agt = {1, ..., k} be a set of agents with a typical element a .
3-7:The language of CTLK consists of formulae ϕ, given as follows: ϕ ::= p | ¬ϕ | ϕ ∧ ϕ | Eγ | Kaϕ γ ::= fϕ | 2 ϕ | ϕU ϕ .
3-8:We will sometimes refer to formulae ϕ as (vanilla) state formulae and to formulae γ as (vanilla) path formulae .
3-9:The semantics of CTLK is based on Kripke models M = Q, R, ∼1, ..., ∼k, π , which include a nonempty set of states Q, a state transition relation R ⊆ Q × Q, epistemic indistinguishability relations ∼a⊆ Q × Q (one per agent), and a valuation of propositions π : Π → P(Q) .
3-10:We assume that relation R is serial and that all ∼a are equivalence relations .
