4 EXTENDING TIME AND KNOWLEDGE WITH PLAUSIBILITY AND BELIEFS :
4-1:WITH PLAUSIBILITY AND BELIEFS In this section we discuss the central concept of this paper, i.e .
4-2:the concept of plausibility .
4-3:First, we outline the idea informally .
4-4:Then, we extend CTLK with the notion of plausibility by adding plausible path operators Pl a and physical path operator Ph to the logic .
4-5:Formula Pl aϕ has the intended meaning: according to agent a, it is plausible that ϕ holds; formula Ph ϕ reads as: ϕ holds in all physically possible scenarios (i.e., even in implausible ones) .
4-6:The plausible path operator restricts statements only to those paths which are defined to be sensible, whereas the physical path operator generates statements about all paths that may theoretically occur .
4-7:Furthermore, we define beliefs on top of plausibility and knowledge, as the facts that an agent would know if he assumed that only plausible things could happen .
4-8:Finally, we discuss related work [7, 8, 20, 18, 16], and compare it with our approach .
4-9:3.1 The Concept of Plausibility It is well known how knowledge (or beliefs) can be modeled with Kripke structures .
4-10:However, it is not so obvious how we can capture knowledge and beliefs in a sensible way in one framework .
4-11:Clearly, there should be a connection between these two notions .
4-12:Our approach is to use the notion of plausibility for this purpose .
4-13:Plausibility can serve as a primitive concept that helps to define the semantics of beliefs, in a similar way as indistinguishability of states (represented by relation ∼a) is the semantic concept that underlies knowledge .
4-14:In this sense, our work follows [7, 20]: essentially, beliefs are what an agent would know if he took only plausible options into account .
4-15:In our approach, however, plausibility is explicitly seen as a temporal property .
4-16:That is, we do not consider states (or possible worlds) to be more plausible than others but rather define some behaviors to be plausible, and others implausible .
4-17:Moreover, behaviors can be formally understood as temporal paths in the Kripke structure modeling a multi agent system .
4-18:An actual notion of plausibility (that is, a particular set of plausible paths) can emerge in many different ways .
4-19:It may result from observations and learning; an agent can learn from its observations and see specific patterns of events as plausible (a lot of people wear black shoes if they wear a suit) .
4-20:Knowledge exchange is another possibility (e.g., an agent a can tell agent b that player c always bluffs when he is smiling) .
4-21:Game theory, with its rationality criteria (undominated strategies, maxmin, Nash equilibrium etc.) is another viable source of plausibility assumptions .
4-22:Last but not least, folk knowledge can be used to establish plausibilityrelated classifications of behavior (players normally want to win a game, people want to live) .
4-23:In any case, restricting the reasoning to plausible possibilities can be essential if we want to make the reasoning feasible, as the space of all possibilities (we call them physical possibilities in the rest of the paper) is exceedingly large in real life .
4-24:Of course, this does not exclude a more extensive analysis in special cases, e.g .
4-25:when our plausibility assumptions do not seem accurate any more, or when the cost of The Sixth Intl .
4-26:Joint Conf .
4-27:on Autonomous Agents and Multi Agent Systems (AAMAS 07) 583 inaccurate assumptions can be too high (as in the case of high budget business decisions) .
4-28:But even in these cases, we usually do not get rid of plausibility assumptions completely we only revise them to make them more cautious.3 To formalize this idea, we extend models of CTLK with sets of plausible paths and add plausibility operators Pl a, physical paths operator Ph , and belief operators Ba to the language of CTLK .
4-29:Now, it is possible to make statements that refer to plausible paths only, as well as statements that regard all paths that may occur in the system .
4-30:3.2 CTLK with Plausibility In this section, we extend the logic of CTLK with plausibility; we call the resulting logic CTLKP .
4-31:Formally, the language of CTLKP is defined as: ϕ ::= p | ¬ϕ | ϕ ∧ ϕ | Eγ | Pl aϕ | Ph ϕ | Kaϕ | Baϕ γ ::= fϕ | 2 ϕ | ϕU ϕ .
4-32:For instance, we may claim it is plausible to assume that a shop is closed after the opening hours, though the manager may be physically able to open it at any time: Pl aA2 (late → ¬open) ∧ Ph E♦ (late ∧ open) .
4-33:The semantics of CTLKP extends that of CTLK as follows .
4-34:Firstly, we augment the models with sets of plausible paths .
4-35:A model with plausibility is given as M = Q, R, ∼1, ..., ∼k, Υ1, ..., Υk, π , where Q, R, ∼1, ..., ∼k, π is a CTLK model, and Υa ⊆ ΛM is the set of paths in M that are plausible according to agent M, we will write ΥM a .
4-36:It seems worth emphasizing that this notion of plausibility is subjective and holistic .
4-37:It is subjective because Υa represents agent a"s subjective view on what is plausible and indeed, different agents may have different ideas on plausibility (i.e., Υa may differ from Υb) .
4-38:It is holistic because Υa represents agent a"s idea of the plausible behavior of the whole system (including the behavior of other agents) .
4-39:Remark 1 .
4-40:In our models, plausibility is also global, i.e., plausibility sets do not depend on the state of the system .
4-41:Investigating systems, in which plausibility is relativized with respect to states (like in [7]), might be an interesting avenue of future work .
4-42:However, such an approach while obviously more flexible allows for potentially counterintuitive system descriptions .
4-43:For example, it might be the case that path λ is plausible in q = λ[0], but the set of plausible paths in q = λ[1] is empty .
4-44:That is, by following plausible path λ we are bound to get to an implausible situation .
4-45:But then, does it make sense to consider λ as plausible? Secondly, we use a non standard satisfaction relation |=P , which we call plausible satisfaction .
