7-1:In this paper a notion of plausible behavior is considered, with the underlying idea that implausible options should be usually ignored in practical reasoning about possible future courses of action
7-2:We add the new notion of plausibility to the logic of CTLK [19], and obtain a language which enables reasoning about what can (or must) plausibly happen
7-3:As a technical device to define the semantics of the resulting logic, we use a non standard satisfaction relation |=P that allows to propagate the current set of plausible paths into subformulae
7-4:Furthermore, we propose a non standard notion of beliefs, defined in terms of indistinguishability and plausibility
7-5:We also propose how plausibility assumptions can be specified in the object language via a plausibility update operator (in a way similar to [13])
7-6:We use this new framework to investigate some important properties of plausibility, knowledge, beliefs, and updates
7-7:In particular, we show that knowledge is an S5 modality, and that beliefs satisfy axioms K45 in general, and KD45 for the class of plausibly serial models
7-8:We also prove that believing in ϕ is knowing that ϕ plausibly holds in all plausibly possible situations
7-9:That is, the relationship between knowledge and beliefs is very natural and reflects the initial intuition precisely
7-10:Moreover, the model checking results from Section 5 show that verification for CTLKP is no more complex than for CTL and CTLK
7-11:We would like to stress that we do not see this contribution as a mere technical exercise in formal logic
7-12:Human agents use a similar concept of plausibility and practical beliefs in their everyday reasoning in order to reduce the search space and make the reasoning feasible
7-13:As a consequence, we suggest that the framework we propose may prove suitable for modeling, design, and analysis resource bounded agents in general
7-14:We would like to thank Juergen Dix for fruitful discussions, useful comments and improvements.
